    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>For a 6-Year-Old Boy, the Series Is but a Dream</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Richard T Mermelstein letter notes his six-year-old boy is likely to fall asleep before a World Series game ends</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''7 Train Awaits: Mets Reach World Series'' (front page, Oct. 17):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''7 Train Awaits: Mets Reach World Series'' (front page, Oct. 17):</p>
        <p>I awoke my 6-year-old son a little past midnight to tell him, ''The Mets won; they're going to the World Series.''</p>
        <p>He, of course, had watched only the first inning, because the television networks and Major League Baseball (seemingly a wholly owned subsidiary of the networks) have scheduled virtually all post-season games to end hours after any schoolchild's bedtime.</p>
        <p>A tiny, sleepy voice whispered ''Yes!'' as he fell back to sleep, confident that he will not see the final inning of a single World Series game this year.</p>
        <p>RICHARD T. MERMELSTEIN  New York, Oct. 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
